type": "string"}, "title": "Paths", "type": "array"}}, "required": ["paths"], "additionalProperties": false}, "strict": false}}, {"type": "function", "function": {"name": "transfer_to_architect", "description": "Delegate system design to the Architect.", "parameters": {"type": "object", "properties": {}, "required": [], "additionalProperties": false}, "strict": true}}, {"type": "function", "function": {"name": "transfer_to_engineer", "description": "Delegate implementation to the Engineer.", "parameters": {"type": "object", "properties": {}, "required": [], "additionalProperties": false}, "strict": true}}, {"type": "function", "function": {"name": "transfer_to_codereviewer", "description": "Delegate code review to the CodeReviewer.", "parameters": {"type": "object", "properties": {}, "required": [], "additionalProperties": false}, "strict": true}}, {"type": "function", "function": {"name": "transfer_to_qa", "description": "Delegate testing and validation to QA.", "parameters": {"type": "object", "properties": {}, "required": [], "additionalProperties": false}, "strict": true}}], "type": "LLMCall", "messages": [{"content": "You are Alice, a seasoned Project Manager.\n\n## Mesh workflow\nThe team operates as a mesh, not a hub-and-spoke.  Once you kick off the\nworkflow, specialists hand off directly to each other in a natural SDLC order:\n\n    You \u2192 Architect \u2192 Engineer \u2192 CodeReviewer \u2192 QA \u2192 You (final report)\n\nSpecialists also loop back without involving you:\n  - CodeReviewer \u2192 Engineer  (if changes are needed)\n  - QA           \u2192 Engineer  (if bugs are found)\n\nYou re-enter the flow only when:\n  1. A specialist explicitly escalates back to you (unclear requirements,\n     blocking issues, or final completion).\n  2. You decide to directly intervene (e.g., reprioritise, split a ticket,\n     bypass design for a hotfix).\n\n## Your responsibilities\n- Understand the user's idea or requirement thoroughly.\n- Break the work into clear, actionable tickets BEFORE delegating.\n- Kick off the workflow by delegating to the Architect (or directly to the\n  Engineer for trivial changes that need no design work).\n- Synthesise all specialist results into a coherent final summary when the\n  project is complete.\n- For each user request, create one or more tickets as SEPARATE FILES on the\n  project board (data/project_board/). The board is a ticketing system, not a\n  single \"whiteboard\" document.\n- Store tickets under: data/project_board/tickets/\n- Maintain a lightweight index at: data/project_board/index.md\n  - The index is a directory of tickets (ID, Title, Status, Owner, Links).\n  - Do not put full ticket content in the index; keep details inside each ticket file.\n- Maintain a simple Kanban-style workflow with statuses:\n  TO DO, IN PROGRESS, IN REVIEW, DONE.\n- Ensure ticket statuses reflect reality as work progresses.\n- Ensure each ticket links to relevant knowledge base docs and code paths.\n- When delegating to specialists, ALWAYS include the exact ticket file path(s)\n  they must update (e.g., data/project_board/tickets/T-20260316-001-short-slug.md).\n- Together with the Architect, document the agreed approach and design for\n  each user request in the knowledge base (data/knowledge_base/).\n\n## Handoff tools available to you\n- transfer_to_Architect    : kick off system design.\n- transfer_to_Engineer     : bypass design and delegate implementation directly.\n- transfer_to_CodeReviewer : request an out-of-band review.\n- transfer_to_QA           : request targeted validation.\n\n## Other tools available to you\n- board_*  : read and write files in the project board (data/project_board/).\n- docs_*   : read documentation and knowledge base files (data/knowledge_base/).\n\n## Rules\n- Never attempt to read or write paths outside these data/ directories.\n- Do NOT write or modify code directly.\n- Always use a transfer_to_* tool to delegate; never just address a specialist\n  by name in plain text.\n- Ticket file naming:\n  - Use stable IDs with sortable filenames, e.g.:\n    - data/project_board/tickets/T-YYYYMMDD-###-short-slug.md\n  - Never overwrite a ticket by reusing an existing ID for a different request.\n- Ticket template (minimum required fields in every ticket file):\n  - ID:\n  - Title:\n  - Status: TO DO | IN PROGRESS | IN REVIEW | DONE\n  - Owner: (role or person)\n  - Description:\n  - Acceptance Criteria: (bulleted, testable)\n  - Tasks: (checklist-style; can reference specialist ownership)\n  - Links: (knowledge base docs and code paths)\n  - Updates / History: (brief timestamped notes as status changes)\n- When creating/updating tickets, keep them small and actionable; split work\n  into multiple tickets when it reduces coupling and improves parallelism.\n- When all tasks are complete, respond with a final summary that begins\n  with the exact text: \"PROJECT COMPLETE\".\n", "role": "system"}, {"role": "user", "name": "user", "content": "Build a CLI Todo App with JSON"}, {"role": "assistant", "tool_calls": [{"id": "call_WT6aYumgPERmkS8svk8mhfl8", "function": {"arguments": "{\"path\": \"data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-001-setup-structure.md\", \"content\": \"ID: T-20231006-001\\nTitle: Setup Project Structure\\nStatus: TO DO\\nOwner: Engineer\\nDescription: Create the basic directory structure for the CLI Todo app.\\nAcceptance Criteria:\\n- Project directories are created (src, tests, etc.).\\n- Basic README file exists.\\n- Initial package.json is created.\\nTasks:\\n- [ ] Create 'src' directory.\\n- [ ] Create 'tests' directory.\\n- [ ] Initialize a package.json file.\\nLinks: N/A\\nUpdates / History: Initial ticket created.\"}", "name": "board_write_file"}, "type": "function"}, {"id": "call_9hPIj9SVaowjSJCcIGBo8TYU", "function": {"arguments": "{\"path\": \"data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-002-json-storage.md\", \"content\": \"ID: T-20231006-002\\nTitle: JSON File Storage Implementation\\nStatus: TO DO\\nOwner: Engineer\\nDescription: Develop functionality to read from and write to a JSON file for storing Todo items.\\nAcceptance Criteria:\\n- JSON file is created and used to store Todo items.\\n- Implement functions to read and write Todo items.\\nTasks:\\n- [ ] Create JSON file structure.\\n- [ ] Implement read functionality.\\n- [ ] Implement write functionality.\\nLinks: N/A\\nUpdates / History: Initial ticket created.\"}", "name": "board_write_file"}, "type": "function"}, {"id": "call_meO5ETee4AJ5Q16g5y7IPI9d", "function": {"arguments": "{\"path\": \"data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-003-cli-commands.md\", \"content\": \"ID: T-20231006-003\\nTitle: CLI Command Implementation\\nStatus: TO DO\\nOwner: Engineer\\nDescription: Implement commands for adding, viewing, and removing Todo items in the CLI.\\nAcceptance Criteria:\\n- Users can add new Todo items from the command line.\\n- Users can view all Todo items from the command line.\\n- Users can remove Todo items by ID from the command line.\\nTasks:\\n- [ ] Implement add command.\\n- [ ] Implement view command.\\n- [ ] Implement remove command.\\nLinks: N/A\\nUpdates / History: Initial ticket created.\"}", "name": "board_write_file"}, "type": "function"}, {"id": "call_uXJ1RkSO2IL1RVsjVpk3ZAHz", "function": {"arguments": "{\"path\": \"data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-004-data-validation.md\", \"content\": \"ID: T-20231006-004\\nTitle: Data Validation\\nStatus: TO DO\\nOwner: Engineer\\nDescription: Ensure that the data being added or removed follows the required format and validation rules.\\nAcceptance Criteria:\\n- Validation checks are implemented for adding Todo items.\\n- Error messages are returned for invalid input.\\nTasks:\\n- [ ] Implement validation checks.\\n- [ ] Create error handling for invalid inputs.\\nLinks: N/A\\nUpdates / History: Initial ticket created.\"}", "name": "board_write_file"}, "type": "function"}, {"id": "call_a2e5c5CR2fFAYXxSuDyLDHIU", "function": {"arguments": "{\"path\": \"data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-005-user-documentation.md\", \"content\": \"ID: T-20231006-005\\nTitle: User Documentation\\nStatus: TO DO\\nOwner: Engineer\\nDescription: Create documentation for how to install and use the CLI Todo app.\\nAcceptance Criteria:\\n- README file contains installation instructions.\\n- README file contains usage instructions for the CLI commands.\\nTasks:\\n- [ ] Write installation instructions.\\n- [ ] Write usage instructions.\\nLinks: N/A\\nUpdates / History: Initial ticket created.\"}", "name": "board_write_file"}, "type": "function"}], "content": "To build a CLI Todo App that utilizes JSON for storage, I will break down the project into clear, actionable tickets. This will enable the team to work on individual components effectively.\n\n### Proposed Tickets for the CLI Todo App\n\n1. **Ticket for Project Structure Setup**\n   - Create the basic directory structure for the CLI Todo app.\n   \n2. **Ticket for JSON File Storage Implementation**\n   - Develop functionality to read from and write to a JSON file for storing Todo items.\n   \n3. **Ticket for CLI Command Implementation**\n   - Implement commands for adding, viewing, and removing Todo items in the CLI.\n   \n4. **Ticket for Data Validation**\n   - Ensure that the data being added or removed follows the required format and validation rules.\n\n5. **Ticket for User Documentation**\n   - Create documentation for how to install and use the CLI Todo app.\n\nWith these tickets in mind, I will now create them in our project board. \n\n### Ticket Format\n\nI'll follow the required ticket format for each one, ensuring they each have a unique ID and all necessary fields filled out.\n\nLet's start by creating each of these tickets now."}, {"content": "Successfully wrote to data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-001-setup-structure.md", "role": "tool", "tool_call_id": "call_WT6aYumgPERmkS8svk8mhfl8"}, {"content": "Successfully wrote to data/project_board/tickets/T-20231006-002-json-st